5. Is SMC the Wrong Approach? ğŸ¤”
You asked if SMC analysis might be the wrong thing to build around. Here's my honest take:

SMC Can Work, BUT:

âœ… Pros:

Institutional logic (follows smart money)
Lower frequency (quality over quantity)
High RR potential (2-5RR possible)
Good for prop firms (low DD, high wins)
âŒ Cons:

Subjective (OB placement varies trader to trader)
Hard to codify (what IS an order block exactly?)
Needs confluence (OB alone isn't enough)
Overfitting risk (too many rules = curve fitting)
My Verdict: SMC is NOT wrong, but needs:

âœ… Clear, objective rules (no "it looks like an OB")
âœ… Multiple confirmations (structure + OB + liquidity + session)
âœ… Backtesting validation (prove it works on historical data)
âœ… Simple first (don't over-complicate)
Alternative Thought: What if we combine:

SMC for context (trend, structure, zones)
Price action for entry (specific candle patterns)
Session filtering (only trade kill zones)
Risk management (prop firm rules enforced)
This is more hybrid - use SMC to find WHERE to trade, price action for WHEN to enter.




